segments.text: Test, test, this is a test.
Today's date is June 13th, 1983.
This is an interview with General Cargill at Texas A&M University, 2 p.m.
This is a test.
Today is June 13, 1983.
I'm interviewing General Cargill at Texas A&M.
This is Terry Anderson.
Let's start off with your early years.
You were born in Waco.
Could you tell us when?
Yes, I was born in 1931 on the 22nd of September.
And I was born in Hillcrest Hospital in Waco, Texas, which is the county seat for McLennan County.
But I was actually, my mother and father were actually living in a little country town south of Waco.
So I claim Eddie, E-D-D-Y, Eddie, Texas as my hometown.
And of course, since that was the closest hospital, that's why I left Waco as my place of birth.
But I've never lived in Waco.
I've always lived, my hometown's always been Eddie.
And that's in the very
southernmost part of McLennan County, which is very near the geographical center of the state.
Could we talk about your parents?
I'd really like to know about their occupation, the type of people that they were, and maybe a little bit about your mom and your dad, their background.
OK. My father was born at Rogers, Texas, which is near Temple.
And I'm not sure what county that's in, but it's just outside of Temple, which is in Bell County.
I've forgotten the year he was born, but he was born in 1896 on August the something.
And he was the eldest of some nine or 10 kids.
Of course, in those days, people had big families.
And they lived on a farm, and I think one or two of his
brothers and maybe one of his sisters died in their early childhood of what we would call today relatively minor things, things like pneumonia or something like that.
But in any event, he grew into manhood as a farm boy.
In addition to the regular farm work, well, that area of the country was heavily wooded at that time, and they did a lot of things like cut and haul wood to the sawmill for lumber.
He was a mule skinner, drove a team of four mules.
And so they lived in that part of the country for a while.
Then they moved up in the northern Texas to a little out from a little community called May Pearl, Texas.
And I'm not real sure just where May Pearl is, but it's up all somewhere south of Dallas, I think.
I'm not sure.
But in any event, at the time they were living there, he joined the...
the National Guard.
And after he'd been in the National Guard for a while, he was called active duty during the First World War.
And I think he, well, their ranks then weren't exactly the same as our ranks are now.
His title was Waggoner.
They found out that he drove mules, was a mule skinner when he was a young man.
When I say young man, I mean 16, 17, 18 years old.
And so they were looking for experienced people that could drive a team of mules, so he was a mule skinner, or a wagoner, was his official military rank.
And he was in the U.S. Army?
He was in the U.S. Army, and this was during the Second World War.
First.
Excuse me, First World War, right.
He never had to go overseas.
He was getting ready to take off for the port of embarkation when the armistice was signed.
So he never saw any duty.
However, he says that from some of the sergeants that he had, he had preferred duty over some of the superiors he served under.
Did he leave Texas?
No.
Or was he trained?
He was trained here in Texas at Camp Bullis, which I believe is in San Antonio.
I'm not sure what camp.
It's still an existing facility of some type.
But in any event, he was discharged from there.
Then he moved to the little town where I was born, Eddy, and went into the wholesale oil business.
He was a Sinclair Oil distributor, which was a, I don't know if you remember the old Sinclair Oil Company.
And I think later on it changed to ARCO.
I think that Atlantic Richfield is a surviving company from the old Sinclair Company.
Their symbol was the dinosaur.
Well, he had a wholesale oil distributing company in the late 20s, and apparently was doing quite well with it and selling primarily to farmers in the McLennan County, Bell County region.
And then, of course, in 1929, the Depression hit.
And people were not able to pay their bills and to make a long story short, he had to shut down his business with lots of accounts receivables on the books.
And this was probably in about 1930, thereabouts.
And of course, I was born in 31 to complicate the situation.
He had been married, I guess, mother and dad had been married almost two years when I was born.
And so...
At that time, he was very active in the Democratic Party.
And in keeping with the patronage system that was in effect at that time, and to maybe some extent still is, he was named the postmaster for the little town of Eddy.
What a stroke of luck.
Was just one of the few cash-paying positions in that whole part of the country.
And so he was the postmaster there throughout my childhood and up until I was a teenager.
And then about 1946, which would have made me about 14 or 15 years old, then he transferred to the rural mail route and was a rural mail carrier.
On the surface, you'd think, well, that's a step down from the postmaster.
But the rural mail carrier's job paid more money.
And plus, he'd get through about 1.30, 2 o'clock in the afternoon.
So he'd have some time off in the afternoon.
And he went ahead and retired as a rural mail carrier.
So he has a federal pension now.
Right.
Both my mother and father still live in Eddy.
And so he retired a few years back.
I've forgotten exactly when.
But he was in the mail service for, well, from around 1930 until, oh, I would say 1975, something like that.
So he had a long time.
in the federal service.
What impact, besides economically, did the Depression have a psychological impact on him in any sense?
I mean, to have a business like that and then to lose it?
I think it affected my mother.
Probably more than my father.
Of course, I'm just surely speculating because being an infant at the time, I really wasn't in a position to observe.
But dad's always been kind of an easy come, easy go kind of a guy that was very adaptable and just was a very happy type person no matter what came.
I do feel that, of course, a small town is a rough place for
a young couple to grow up in, because there's nothing to do.
And I would think probably that it had an impact on my mother more than my father, although I wouldn't.
I just wouldn't know.
Disappointment, probably.
Feeling that, why me?
No, that kind of deal.
However, in a town, in a small country town,
in our town especially, one of the chief social activities was the church.
And our town was split between the Southern Baptist and the Methodist.
And there were a few others, but those were the two predominant churches there.
And so I would think that in a small community like that, everybody knows everybody else, knows all their kids, all their family histories.
It's just like one big family.
Well, the depression hit everybody about the same.
You know, everybody was just flat broke and, you know, I mean, literally helping each other by giving them food so they wouldn't starve, those kinds of things.
Now, of course, I didn't experience it myself, but I've heard about it so much that I feel like I've lived it.
And when I say I didn't experience it myself, I didn't experience those early days, you know, where really the crash hit.
And, of course, as I say, we fared much better than most due to my
due to the fact that my dad had the federal job, which was a rarity.
Because there was just one.
And there were a couple of clerks involved.
But for a reasonably good paying job, that was the only one in that part of the country.
So we fared much better than most.
But my point is that even though we were relatively poor, I never knew we were poor because everybody else was in the same boat.
I didn't have to envy the Joneses because there were no Joneses.
Everybody was in the same boat.
Does that make any sense what I'm trying to say?
Yeah, absolutely.
Uniformity.
Yeah.
And so that's not a bad word.
We were all uniformly poor.
And I've noticed that from many men who
went to A&M during the 1930s and who had many of the similar experiences.
I've heard a lot of this type of a statement before.
Being that everybody's in the same boat, you all feel sort of equal.
Yeah, that's right.
There's sort of an egalitarian of poverty.
Sure.
Now, I might tell you a little bit about my mother, which would tie in with this.
I want you to.
OK.
My mother was born Maudie Caroline Cole.
In fact, I don't believe I told you my father's full name.
C-O-L-E. My father's full name is Willie Newton Cargill.
And Maudie Caroline.
N-E-W-T-O-N. N-E-W-T-O-N.
Right.
Willie Newton.
And my mother was born, you know, shame to tell you, but I'm not sure where she was born.
I think Paris, Texas.
And...
She was from a family that had come out of Arkansas, and I'm not sure where before that.
But they, too, were a farm family, big family, three or four girls and two or three boys.
Most of them are dead now.
My mother has two living old maid sisters and one living brother, and the rest of the family is deceased.
They were farmers.
And I know that they came from Arkansas and lived in Oklahoma for a while.
And I don't know if they came to Paris.
Well, they must have, because my mother lived in Oklahoma.
So they probably came from Arkansas to Paris, Texas, where my mother was born.
And then they moved to Oklahoma.
And my mother spent some of her childhood there, lived in a log cabin type of a house with an upstairs area.
Then they moved to Texas, up near Eddy.
And that's where my father met her, I guess.
But in any event, she went through high school.
And then she went in the nurse's training.
Two of her sisters, the two sisters that are still living are both retired registered nurses.
And she went in the nurse's training at San Antonio, at the Texas State Hospital there.

And apparently back in those days, a lot of people performed the nurse's training at the Texas State Hospital, which is a mental institution, of course, at the present time, and I presume was at that time.
But she didn't finish her nurse's training.
She got married to dad before she finished her nurse's training.
Before she, okay, now some of this is going to kind of, I'm going to have to go back and catch up as I remember things.
Before mother went into nurse's training, she was a school teacher.
Now, back in those days, you didn't have to have a college degree, which you never got.
She had two years of college at Mary Harden Baylor University at Belton, Texas, in Bell County.
But after she got out of school, after she finished two years of school at Mary Harden Baylor, then she was a schoolteacher at a little country town out west of Uvalde called Regan Wells, Texas.
Just a little bitty place, but it's still there.
A lot of people down in that part of the country knows where Regan Wells is.
So she taught school at Regan Wells for a while.
And then she went in the nurse's training.
And then she met dad and married and dropped out of nurse's training.
And then she was a housewife.
In those days, there was some.

I hesitate to use the word stigma because that's not the word I'm looking for, but there was some hesitancy for women to work, especially some of the old-time guys, like my dad, for example, felt that if the wife worked, then that was a sign that he couldn't adequately provide for herself.
It was an ego thing.
Thank goodness that's behind us because my wife works, and I don't know what I'd do without it.
But in any event, she was a housewife, and...
So they were married probably in the early 20s?
They were married, yeah.
When he owned the company, mid-20s probably?
He was in the oil business, I would say, from about 1925 until about 1930, somewhere along in there.
Of course, the crash was in 1929.
I would say that he and mother married, I was born in 1931, and they had been married about,
18 months.
So counting back from September of 31, back 18 months would have made it about 1929.
So they married probably just months before the crash hit.
And of course, at that time, Daddy had bought a house.
And Dad had been married previously.
He was married to, I don't even remember the lady's name.
But he was married for a short time, and they divorced.
and my mother had only been married one time.
But in any event, he had a nice house, one of the nicer homes in town.
It's still there, incidentally, where I spent my early childhood.

And, of course, after Daddy went in the post office, which was just only a couple blocks down the street, I can remember he'd come home at lunchtime, and we'd have lunch together and take a little nap on the floor in the hallway.
That was before the days of air conditioning.
So we'd put a pallet down on the
in the hallway and open all the doors, and then there would be a draft through there to keep you cool.
But in any event, the mother was a housewife up until the beginning of the Second World War.
And then she went to work for Blue Bonnet Ordnance Plant, which is in Belton, excuse me, which is in McGregor, Texas, working in an ordinance plant, making bombs.
I think mother worked there about two and a half, maybe three years.
during the war as a patriotic effort, but also to help with family finances because, of course, I never remember a time when we had all the money we needed, just like most families.
So I thought that was an interesting thing, that Mother was involved with the ordinance work.
I've forgotten what size bombs they made, but they were conventional weapons, obviously, at that time.
just the regular bombs.
And then right after the war, or right before the end of the war, she came back home?
Yes.
Yeah, they closed down the plant after the war, and then she came back home, and then she's never worked since then.
I recall that she might have done some part-time sales work at Christmas time at one of the stores in Waco.
Eddie's only about 18 miles south of Waco, right on the interstate, Interstate 35.
Used to be, well, it still is, Highway 81, US 81.
Sure.
But now it's Interstate 35.
It goes north and south.
But with the exception of some part-time work at some of the department stores, like at Christmastime or rush times, she never did work.
Can you tell me about your dad's education?
Yes.
Dad had very little education.
As I recall, he only went through about the fifth or sixth grade.
And he's an extremely well-educated man.
But he did it by reading and studying, a lot of self-study, but formal education.
As I recall, he only went through about the fifth and sixth grade.
Being the eldest in a large family, well, he dropped out of school at an early age to help on the family farm.
He, throughout his adult life, was very, very active in the Masonic Lodge.
And it's been kind of tradition in our family to, you know,
became a Mason.
That was kind of like becoming a Southern Baptist.
It was just expected and something you look forward to.
I'm an active Mason.
Through his Masonic work, he's done a lot of reading, a lot of public speaking.
When he was the postmaster, the postmaster in these little country towns back in the 30s was really kind of the center of political influence.
When all the politicians would come through, Dad would be the first person they'd go see because he could influence a lot of votes and so forth.
Now, when Jim Farley was the postmaster general, Jim Farley used to come through town.
He'd always stop and see Dad.
And Dad was an excellent public speaker, taught Sunday school class for years.
And through his speaking in connection with Masonic Lodge, he would just use his flawless English and just
I consider a very well-educated man, even though he only had a very limited formal education.
How would you say he was a Democrat?
In what sense was he a Democrat?
I mean, there's so many different types in America.
Was he a Lyndon Johnson man?
Was he a FDR Democrat?
He was basically an FDR Democrat.
Of course, keep in mind
The time and place.
I would say if I had to put a label on him now, looking back, I would say he's a conservative Democrat.
Although in those days, the liberal and conservative labels hadn't really been developed yet.
You were either Republican or Democrat.
And when I was raised to believe that Republican was almost like some kind of social disease, we had one or two Republicans in town.
And when they'd go down the street, everybody's like, hey, there goes that Republican.
I thought the guy had something wrong with him for a long time before I realized that this was a political party.
And it's really odd, but people just really, if you were a Republican, you were an outcast in that part of the country.
So basically, the vast majority of people were Democrats.
And then, of course, you got into your primaries is where the real infighting.
Because until this good day, in many parts of Texas, as you probably know, being nominated by the Democratic Party is tantamount to election.
And that's probably true still at that little voting box.
I doubt if it's going Republican ever.
And it may not ever go Republican, although I personally vote for the
for the candidate as opposed to a party.
I'm a registered Democrat, but that doesn't mean that I always vote a straight ticket by any means.
But in any event, he's...
So you would consider him a conservative, basically?
I would consider him basically a conservative.
And then what impact did his political beliefs have on you?
I would think that due to the austere conditions that we were living in financially, that
I became a very conservative from a fiscal standpoint.
Due to a lot of human suffering that went on around me, I became somewhat liberal as far as people are concerned.
Now, the two are not always compatible.
And so I would consider myself growing out of the conservative fiscal environment and the liberalism from human suffering that was around me,
that I would almost label myself as, well, I would have to label myself as a conservative Democrat.
Liberal on people programs, but only to the extent that you can afford them.
And in other words, I'm getting in deep water here now.
Let me see if I can express myself so that it comes through the way I want it to.
I feel very strongly that everyone should be able to, that no one should starve, that no one should not have clothing, that no one should be without shelter.
But I don't go much past that as far as the welfare programs.
Now, how you draw the line between getting the freeloaders off and helping people that legitimately need help
It's a fine line, and it almost has to be something that is a judgment call on somebody's part.
But, you know, I would do anything to keep anyone from being hungry because I've seen people hungry before.
So political ideology for you is much more complex than just saying you're a liberal or you're a conservative.
It is.
Labels get you in trouble.
Well, they sure do.
Labels get you in trouble.
Yeah.
But I would say that fiscally, I'm a very staunch conservative.
I just don't believe in spending money you don't have.
It's because sooner or later, payday's coming.
And it's so much better to don't bite off more than you can chew and go ahead and behave yourself responsibly than it is to try to get well after you really get sick.
I think that's the trouble that this country's been in.
I think that we've gone through a real
rough recession, but I think it's something that we had to do to get over some of the problems we had.
And so I feel real good about our economy and our country right now, better than I have for a long time.
That's not to say we're well, a long way from being well.
Well, even with these deficits, that must bother you.
Oh, it does, very much, very much.
I don't know how closely you follow
the advocacy of Phil Graham, but I'm a real Phil Graham guy.
I think Phil's got it pretty well lined up right, and I think a lot of people have.
I'm very strongly for a constitutional amendment that would prohibit deficit budgets.
It's worked well for us here in Texas.
You may or may not know we've got that here.
We've had it for years.
As a result, we're one of the strongest states in the union as far as from a fiscal responsibility standpoint.
And I'm convinced that we don't have deficits for one reason and one reason only, and that is the Constitution won't permit it.
If our politicians had the authority, they'd spin us blind just the way they're doing in Washington.
So that's why I'm so strongly for a constitutional amendment to prevent deficit budgets at the federal level.
Of course, Phil's working very hard for that, and I hope he's successful.
I'll do what I can to help him.
Tell me about your mother's political ideology.
Was she very involved, or did she get involved, or did she leave it to the men?
I don't recall mothers being involved too much in state or federal politics.
Now, she's always had a strong interest in local politics.
By that, I'm talking about maybe like members of the school board.
Sure.
Since it was an unincorporated city, we didn't have a city council or anything like that.
We do now, but not at that time.
As I recall, Mother ran for the school board one time because she was upset about something.
Mother is a crusader type.
If she doesn't like something, she doesn't just ignore it and go on her way.
She tries to go fix it.
And as a result, she ran for the school board one time.
She was defeated, but at least she got it out of her system that she made the effort.
But I don't recall Mother ever being
too keen on state or national politics other than the fact that she had an interest in it because of dad's position in town or what have you.
Who is the authority in the household?
I would say that's a hard question to answer.
I would say it's more or less a sharing type of an arrangement.
Mother and Dad always talked about things together.
Dad was very prone to let Mother do what she wanted to do up to a point.
But he had the ability to put his foot down and say, we're not going to do that.
And then she knew to pull in because Dad had finally made a decision.
But he was the kind of guy that really didn't matter too much.
He was perfectly willing to do pretty well what Mother wanted to do.
And for example, in discipline, mother nearly always was a disciplinarian in the family with me.
And I was the only child for a long time.
I was 15, 16 years old before my second brother came along.
I'll tell you about that in a minute.
But if there was any spanking or whipping, mother nearly always did it.
But if I really need punishing bad, then dad laid the belt on me.
And I don't think he ever whipped me over two or three times.
But I remember those two or three times pretty well.
And of course, Mother was the disciplinarian and more spankings and switchings than anything else.
And I didn't get them unless I really needed them.
But I was a mischievous kid, the way most kids are.
But I think pretty well disciplined.
At least everyone says that I was.
Well, you mentioned before that there were two types in your town.
There were either Southern Baptists or there were Methodists.
What was your family and what role did religion have in your upbringing?
We were Southern Baptists and are to this day.
My wife was from a similar type background from a religious standpoint, Southern Baptist, so we married in the Southern Baptist Church, still members of the First Baptist Church here in Bryan.
The church...
played a very major role in my early childhood and all through my life and still does.
I don't know how much you know about Southern Baptists, but it's a fundamentalist type religion.
And I believe the Bible pretty well literally.
Of course, there's a lot of people in the denomination that are breaking away from that to some extent.
There's always argumentation.
Yeah, always argument.
Was the world really created?
Six days and on the seventh day will God rest.
My concept of God has changed over a period of time.
But back in those days, it was very dogmatic.
There was no room for latitude.
It was A, B, C, black and white.
And I don't guess the church ever opened that I wasn't there on the front row.
I was a song leader in the church when I was a younger man.
I played then and still do the piano.
And occasionally I would play a special number in front of the church or play the hymns while the church had the song service.
I was very active as a Sunday school teacher and in what we call the training union, which was the Sunday night time activity.
Those early religious teachings, up until the time I left to come to college, that was just a given.
There was never any question about are we going to church Sunday or are we not.
We were always there.
Were your parents active also?
Yes.
Dad was always a Sunday school teacher.
Mother was always there.
I don't recall if she ever taught any classes or not.
I'm not real sure whether she did or not.
She was not the type that liked to get in front of a group and talk too much.
But dad was.
He was kind of the ham of the family, still is.
Loves to get up in front of a group of people and talk, and will at the drop of a hat.
And he's 87 now.

But in any event, to answer your question, the church had a very profound impact on my life, developed a lot of my philosophies about how you deal with people, your respect for individuals, respect for life, respect for property.
Most of my moral teachings were, of course,
The home was just an extension of the things I learned in church.
And so it's difficult for me to say that I learned it in church or I learned it at home because they all melded together.
But to answer your question, the church, yes, had a very strong impact on my life.
childhood, youth, and all my whole life, and thus today.
OK. Now, if I asked you to characterize, I mean to say what type of characters your parents were, could you give me sort of a rundown?
I mean, you've talked around this now for a while.
I would say that my father was a very strong but quiet person.
that avoided controversy when possible, but if he got in a position where he had to take a stand, he'd always take it, and a strong one.
Whereas Mother, on the other hand, was argumentative to some extent.
I'm using past tense like they're gone.
They both still fit this category.
Mother would argue for the sake of argument, and at the drop of a hat would disagree with anyone.
And by the same token, she didn't carry that too far.
She saw that a rift or a problem was developing with one of her neighbors or one of her kinfolks.
Well, then she knew when to pull in her horns.
She was the more aggressive of the two as far as being an outspoken domineering.
If you logged conversation, dad would probably talk 20% of the time and mother 80% of the time.
if that makes any sense.
But very loving, affectionate couple.
I would say that as the years went by and my two other brothers came along, and I mentioned that we got an interesting situation there I'll tell you about.
Because of the influence of the kids and the parents
the requirement of time on mother's part, I think that probably mother and dad grew further apart as a result of having the three boys than they were, as I recall them, in my early childhood.
In other words, it was an outward show of affection frequently when I was a younger kid.
But I don't recall too much of that in the later years, although they hugged and kissed.
Two more young children.
Yeah.
Right.
And of course, I'm sure it's just because of the time involved in raising a child.
But in any event, when I was about 15 or 16, mother and daddy were still relatively young at that time.
And the doctor had told mother that she couldn't have any more children because of some physical problems she had.
So they had an opportunity to adopt my middle-sized brother.
and got him when I think he was six weeks old.
And his name is Stephen Lee Cargill.
And we had him, I guess, probably about a year and a half, maybe two years.
And then lo and behold, my mother became pregnant with my younger brother.
And I understand afterwards that that happens occasionally.
I don't know how frequently it happens, but it does happen.
But the conditions, her physical conditions, whatever prevented her from conceiving,

cleared up and so quite unexpectedly she became pregnant with my younger brother so I have two brothers middle-sized adopted brother and then my younger brother who's the natural brother and what do they do my middle-sized brother graduated from from the school we have a there are two little towns they're Bruceville which is just two miles north of Eddy and they have a consolidated school district which is between the two towns Bruceville Eddy
And he graduated from Bruceville High School.
Excuse me, what am I saying?
Bruceville Eddy High School.
And then he went to Southwest Texas State University for about a year and a half, two years.
And then he dropped out of college and went to work for KCEN TV station in Temple, Texas, which covers this broadcast area, Channel 6.
And he still works for them.
Oh, really?
What does he do?
He was a production coordinator.
working on commercials, you know, the actual production and running cameras and just utility type work for several years.
Then he had an opportunity to go into marketing, selling commercials and so forth.
So he's been a marketing man for KCEN now for, I guess, at least five years.
And he calls on the Temple Belton area and enjoys it and probably go ahead and make a career out of the TV business.
My younger brother
He graduated from Bruce Liddy and went to school at North Texas University.
Let me see.
Yes, okay.
He graduated from North Texas State University in accounting.
In the 60s sometime.
Yes.
I'd be hesitant to guess what year, but in the 60s.
And then he got out of school and went to work for Lone Star Steel Company in Dallas.
They had a plant at Dangerfield, Texas.
And he worked in the home office and their accounting office and then their insurance benefits program, what have you.
And then he left them and went back to school and got a master's degree in accounting.
Then he got out and did.
And then after that, he got his CPA.
So then he got out and did some private CPA practice.
And also, I'm not real sure just what he did, but it was a relatively short period of time.
And then he was married at some time.
In the meantime, he's since divorced, has one child.
Jason is about, oh, I would say 11, 12 years old now.
They just divorced a couple years ago, a year and a half.
But in any event, then he went back to the University of Missouri and has completed coursework on his PhD in accounting.
And he's now teaching school at East Texas State University while he's writing his dissertation.
And he should finish his dissertation by December.
Hopefully the degree will be granted in December.
And then he'll continue on as a college professor.
That's what he wants to do the rest of his life is to teach accounting.
It seems somewhat unusual that you became a general and neither of your brothers even went into the military.
They were both of age during the Vietnam conflict.
My little brother did.
It's almost a comical story.
My mother was afraid he was going to get drafted and she wanted him to be in the Air Force so she kept
on him to volunteer for the Air Force.
